The error message you're receiving is caused by a lack of a comparison operator (`==`) that can compare an `Int17Matrix3D` object with an `int`. When you use `ASSERT_EQ(matrix(1, 1, 1), 5);`, the `ASSERT_EQ` macro expects both operands to be comparable using `==`. However, in your `Int17Matrix3D` class, there is no such operator defined.

To fix this issue, you need to add comparison operators to your class. Below is an example of how to add an `operator==` to your class to compare `Int17Matrix3D` objects and `int` values.

Firstly, add the declaration of the `operator==` in the `Int17Matrix3D` class:

```cpp
// Inside the Int17Matrix3D class
friend bool operator==(const Int17Matrix3D& lhs, int32_t rhs);
friend bool operator==(int32_t lhs, const Int17Matrix3D& rhs);
```

Then, implement them outside of the class:

```cpp
bool operator==(const Int17Matrix3D& lhs, int32_t rhs) {
  return lhs.ToDec(lhs.arr_, lhs.current_index_) == rhs;
}

bool operator==(int32_t lhs, const Int17Matrix3D& rhs) {
  return lhs == rhs.ToDec(rhs.arr_, rhs.current_index_);
}
```

You should also handle the case where the two matrices being compared should be of the same size. If they have different dimensions, they should not be equal. Similarly, you might want to implement `operator!=` as well for inequality comparison.

Make sure the `ToDec` function and `current_index_` member variable can be accessed by these friend functions if necessary. Adjust their accessibility accordingly in the class definition if required.

With these operators added to your class, the `ASSERT_EQ` macro should work without errors since it will now be able to compare `Int17Matrix3D` objects with `int` values correctly. Make sure to apply similar logic if you need to compare two `Int17Matrix3D` objects.

Finally, make sure you have `#include <cstring>` in your headers to provide declarations for `std::memset` and `std::memcpy` functions.

