No, you should not remove the assignment operator `operator=` even though you have a copy constructor. While they can seem similar because they both handle copying data from one object to another, they serve different purposes and are used in different contexts within C++.

Here's a summary of their different roles:

- **Copy constructor**: It is called when a new object is created from an existing object, as a copy of the existing object. Examples of this include passing an object by value to a function, returning an object from a function by value, or explicitly using the copy constructor to initialize a new object with the state of an existing object.

- **Assignment operator (`operator=`)**: It is used when you want to overwrite the existing state of an object with the state of another existing object. This usually happens after both objects have already been constructed.

Both the copy constructor and the assignment operator can be called by numerous features and mechanisms of the language, including when using STL containers that might require elements to be copied or assigned during reallocations, sort operations, etc.

Another important distinction is that the assignment operator typically needs to handle self-assignment (when an object is assigned to itself) and must properly release and manage resources that the object already owns, such as dynamically allocated memory. It usually follows the "copy-and-swap" idiom or carefully orders operations to be exception-safe and manage resources correctly.

So, even though you have correctly implemented a copy constructor, you still need to properly implement the assignment operator to handle assignment of objects after their construction.

Here's your existing assignment operator with some additional safety checks to prevent potential memory leaks in the case of self-assignment:

```cpp
Int17Matrix3D& Int17Matrix3D::operator=(const Int17Matrix3D& other) {
  if (this != &other) {
    // Allocate new memory and copy the elements from other to temp
    int32_t* temp = new int32_t[kNumLenght_ * other.width_ * other.height_ * other.depth_];
    std::memcpy(temp, other.arr_, kNumLenght_ * other.width_ * other.height_ * other.depth_ * sizeof(int32_t));

    // Delete the old array and assign the newly allocated array
    delete[] arr_;
    arr_ = temp;
    width_ = other.width_;
    height_ = other.height_;
    depth_ = other.depth_;
  }
  return *this;
}
```

It's also common to check for self-assignment in the assignment operator to ensure that objects are not trying to assign to themselves, which can lead to issues such as deleted resources still being referenced. This is what the initial `if (this != &other)` check accomplishes.

Чтобы решить эту задачу без использования стандартных ассоциативных контейнеров (как map или set), можно воспользоваться хэш-таблицей с открытой адресацией или массивом для подсчета числа повторений каждого файла. Поскольку в задаче гарантируется, что названия файлов различны внутри одного списка, можно объединить все списки в один и использовать хэш-таблицу для учета количества каждого названия файла.

